+# Meta Note: Exploration 001
+
+## What worked
+
+- Starting from the predecessor packet non-canonicity result, instead of assuming the new sign clue deserved a fresh quantitative phase, kept the strategy honest. The first real question was object stability, not sign optimization.
+- The right stress test was cheap and decisive: ask whether the new sign functionals survive harmless representative changes and packet refinements before launching any `(Leak, SD_part, SD_target)` computation.
+- Treating the singleton sign clue as a clue about mechanism shape, rather than as evidence that canonization had already been solved, prevented the mission from re-running the old packet branch under sharper notation.
+
+## What to carry forward
+
+- A global packet sign statistic is not mission-ready unless it is invariant under the natural conjugate-pair quotient. If the statistic requires choosing one representative from `{(k,sigma), (-k,-sigma)}`, canonicity is still open.
+- Desired-edge heterochirality functionals only become canonical after the exact target-triad set is fixed independently of harmless packet refinement. Otherwise `SD_target` and `Leak` move together.
+- If a follow-on mission adds new observables to the same packet family without shrinking or canonizing the support, predecessor packet negatives may already settle it. Check that before authorizing Phase 1 computations.
+
+## Execution note
+
+- The launched explorer hit the familiar skeleton-buffering stall and never wrote the synthesis back into `REPORT.md` or `REPORT-SUMMARY.md`. Manual recovery was straightforward because the source trail had already converged cleanly on the canonicity defect.
